article.headline: Los Angeles sinks 14-of-15 free throws in win
article.linkText: Sparks go to line to hold off Fever down the stretch
article.story:
INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- This time, the Los Angeles Sparks got it
right.

Two days after a 25-point lead disappeared in a 79-73 loss to
Detroit, the Sparks survived a second-half challenge to edge the
Indiana Fever 61-58 Tuesday night.

WNBA scoring leader Chamique Holdsclaw had 17 points and Tamika
Whitmore completed a three-point play with 41 seconds to go for the
victory.

"We really gutted this one out. It was a disappointing loss at
Detroit," Holdsclaw said. "It was not good for the morale of this
team."

Whitmore finished with 15 points. Her offensive rebound, layup
and free throw ended the scoring.

"I just thought to myself that if the rebound came off on the
weak side I would just go up strong," Whitmore said. "And if they
were going to blow the whistle, they would blow the whistle."

Still, the win wasn't secured until Indiana's Tully Bevilaqua's
3-point shot from the corner bounced off the rim at the buzzer.

Whitmore said the players put the Detroit game behind them.

"It was out of our minds," she said.

The team realized the 13 turnovers in the first half against
Indiana were too many.

"We knew we had to come out and execute," she said.

Los Angeles beat Indiana for the seventh time in eight games
despite 21 turnovers, which led to 16 Fever points.

The Sparks (8-6) did help itself by making 14 of 15 free throws,
while Indiana (8-5) was 9-of-10 from the line.

"We've had some bad nights where we didn't shoot it well from
the line. Tonight was a good night," Los Angeles coach Henry Bibby
said.

Indiana, which lost for the first time in seven home games this
season, battled back from 10 points down in the second half to tie
the game five times.

Three consecutive 3-pointers by Indiana produced a 41-all tie,
and the Sparks had two more five-point leads before a 3-pointer by
Bevilaqua knotted the game at 56 with 4:15 to go.

A steal by Tamecka Dixon followed by her 17-foot jumper gave the
Sparks a 58-56 lead before Indiana tied the game for the last time
at 58.

Kelly Miller led Indiana with 12 points and Bevilaqua had 11,
including three 3-pointers.

The first half was tight with seven ties and seven lead changes.
Los Angeles opened its biggest edge of the half with nine
consecutive points to lead 29-22 before going scoreless in the
final 3:31 to lead 29-25 at the break.

Indiana shot 29 percent in the first half, hitting just 10 of 35
shots.

"We didn't play well enough to win," coach Brian Winters said.

Indiana shot better from 3-point range (7-for-21) than it did
from inside the arc (14-for-46).

"We had some good looks. We just couldn't knock them down,"
Miller said. "We did a good job defensively. Tonight just wasn't
our night."

Nikki Teasley contributed 10 points to the victory and Lisa
Leslie had 11 rebounds. Tamika Catchings scored 10 points for
Indiana, but was only four of 17 from the field.
